            <section class="prose">
              <h2>How this T-bill yield calculator works</h2>
              <p>
                Treasury bills (T-bills) are short-term government securities
                sold at a discount and redeemed at face value. They pay no
                coupons, so your return comes entirely from the difference
                between the purchase price and the face value at maturity.
              </p>
              <p>
                This calculator lets you start from either the
                <strong>quoted discount rate</strong> or the
                <strong>price</strong> and computes:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>Money-market <strong>discount yield</strong></li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Investment rate</strong> based on the amount you
                  actually invest
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Bond-equivalent yield (BEY)</strong> for comparison
                  with coupon bonds
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Effective annual yield</strong> assuming reinvestment
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>Key inputs</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Face value (par)</strong> – usually $1,000 or $100 per
                  bill.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Price</strong> – quoted per 100 of par (e.g., 98.50 =
                  $985 for $1,000 par).
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Discount rate</strong> – money-market discount yield
                  quoted in T-bill auctions.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Settlement and maturity dates</strong> – used to
                  compute the exact days to maturity.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Day-count basis</strong> – Actual/360 or Actual/365
                  (US) or Actual/365 (Canada).
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>Formulas used</h2>

              <h3>1. Days to maturity</h3>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <code>Days = (Maturity date − Settlement date)</code>
              </div>
              <p>
                The calculator uses calendar days between settlement and
                maturity. Weekends and holidays are not adjusted, which is
                standard for yield formula demonstrations (actual settlement
                conventions may differ slightly).
              </p>

              <h3>2. Price from discount rate</h3>
              <p>
                If you start from the quoted discount yield \( d \) (in
                decimal), the price per 100 of par is:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <code>Price = 100 × (1 − d × Days / 360)</code>
              </div>

              <h3>3. Discount yield from price</h3>
              <p>
                Given price per 100 of par, the money-market discount yield is:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <code>d = (100 − Price) / 100 × (360 / Days)</code>
              </div>

              <h3>4. Investment rate (simple annualized yield)</h3>
              <p>
                The investment rate (sometimes called the
                <em>investment yield</em> or <em>coupon-equivalent yield</em>)
                is based on the <strong>amount invested</strong> (price) rather
                than face value:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <code>
                  Investment&nbsp;Rate = (Face − PriceAmount) / PriceAmount ×
                  (BasisDays / Days)
                </code>
              </div>
              <p>
                where <code>BasisDays</code> is 360 or 365 depending on the
                selected day-count convention, and <code>PriceAmount</code> is
                the dollar price for one bill:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <code>PriceAmount = Face × Price / 100</code>
              </div>

              <h3>5. Bond-equivalent yield (BEY)</h3>
              <p>
                To compare a T-bill with a coupon bond that pays interest
                semiannually, we convert the simple annual yield into a
                bond-equivalent yield:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <code>
                  BEY = 2 × [ (1 + InvestmentRate × Days / BasisDays)^(BasisDays
                  / (2 × Days)) − 1 ]
                </code>
              </div>
              <p>
                This approximates a semiannual compounding structure similar to
                coupon bonds.
              </p>

              <h3>6. Effective annual yield (EAY)</h3>
              <p>
                The effective annual yield assumes you can reinvest at the same
                rate over a full year, compounding the holding period return:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <code>
                  Holding&nbsp;Period&nbsp;Return = (Face − PriceAmount) /
                  PriceAmount
                  <br />
                  EAY = (1 + Holding&nbsp;Period&nbsp;Return)^(BasisDays / Days)
                  − 1
                </code>
              </div>

              <h2>Worked example</h2>
              <p>Suppose you buy a 91-day US T-bill with:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>Face value = $1,000</li>
                <li>Price = 98.50 (so you pay $985)</li>
                <li>Days to maturity = 91</li>
                <li>Basis = Actual/365</li>
              </ul>

              <p><strong>1. Holding period return</strong></p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <code>
                  PriceAmount = 1,000 × 98.50 / 100 = 985<br />
                  HPR = (1,000 − 985) / 985 ≈ 0.015228
                </code>
              </div>

              <p><strong>2. Investment rate</strong></p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <code>
                  Investment&nbsp;Rate ≈ 0.015228 × (365 / 91) ≈ 0.0611 = 6.11%
                </code>
              </div>

              <p><strong>3. Effective annual yield</strong></p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <code> EAY = (1 + 0.015228)^(365 / 91) − 1 ≈ 6.29% </code>
              </div>

              <h2>US vs Canadian T-bill yields</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>US T-bills</strong> are typically quoted on a discount
                  basis using a 360-day year.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Canadian T-bills</strong> usually use an Actual/365
                  convention for yields.
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                If you are comparing yields from sources like the US Treasury,
                Bloomberg, or the Bank of Canada, make sure you select the same
                day-count basis and yield definition (discount vs investment vs
                bond-equivalent).
              </p>

              <h2>Limitations</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>Assumes single-payment T-bills with no coupons.</li>
                <li>
                  Uses calendar days between settlement and maturity; actual
                  market conventions may adjust for weekends/holidays.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Assumes reinvestment at the same rate for effective annual
                  yield.
                </li>
              </ul>
            </section>

            <!-- FAQ -->
            <section class="mt-8">
              <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-4">T-bill yield FAQ</h2>
              <div class="space-y-4" id="faq-container">
                <div class="border border-gray-200 rounded-lg">
                  <button
                    class="w-full text-left px-4 py-3 flex justify-between items-center faq-question"
                  >
                    <span class="font-medium text-gray-800"
                      >What is a T-bill yield?</span
                    >
                    <span class="text-gray-500 text-sm">+</span>
                  </button>
                  <div
                    class="px-4 pb-3 hidden faq-answer text-sm text-gray-700"
                  >
                    T-bill yield is the annualized return you earn from buying a
                    Treasury bill at a discount and holding it to maturity.
                    Because T-bills pay no coupons, the yield comes entirely
                    from the difference between the purchase price and the face
                    value, scaled to a yearly rate using a specific day-count
                    convention.
                  </div>
                </div>

                <div class="border border-gray-200 rounded-lg">
                  <button
                    class="w-full text-left px-4 py-3 flex justify-between items-center faq-question"
                  >
                    <span class="font-medium text-gray-800"
                      >What is the difference between discount yield and
                      investment rate?</span
                    >
                    <span class="text-gray-500 text-sm">+</span>
                  </button>
                  <div
                    class="px-4 pb-3 hidden faq-answer text-sm text-gray-700"
                  >
                    Discount yield is based on the bill’s face value and a
                    360-day year, which is how T-bills are quoted in money
                    markets. Investment rate (or investment yield) is based on
                    the actual amount you invest (the price) and often uses a
                    365-day year. Investment rate is more appropriate when
                    comparing T-bills to other investments like bank deposits or
                    coupon bonds.
                  </div>
                </div>

                <div class="border border-gray-200 rounded-lg">
                  <button
                    class="w-full text-left px-4 py-3 flex justify-between items-center faq-question"
